{"title_page": "Robert Steadward", "text_new": "{{Short description|Canadian sports administrator}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name        = Robert Steadward\n| image       = Robert Steadward IFAPA Inaugural Steadward Talks.jpg\n| caption     = Steadward at the IFAPA Inaugural Steadward Talks in 2019\n| honorific-suffix = [[Order of Canada|OC]] [[Alberta Order of Excellence|AOE]]\n| office      = 1st President of the [[International Paralympic Committee]]\n| term_start  = 1989\n| term_end    = 2001\n| successor   = [[Philip Craven]]\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1946|5|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Eston, Saskatchewan]], Canada\n| nationality = Canadian\n| education   = [[Bachelor of Physical Education|BPhEd]], Master's, PhD\n| alma_mater  = [[University of Alberta]]<br>[[University of Oregon]]\n| occupation  = Sports administrator, professor, sports scientist, author\n| known_for   = [[Canadian Paralympic Committee]], [[International Paralympic Committee]]\n| awards      = {{hlist|[[Alberta Sports Hall of Fame]] (1984)|[[Order of Canada]] (1999)|[[Canadian Disability Hall of Fame]] (2002)|[[Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal]] 2002)|[[Canada's Sports Hall of Fame]] (2007)|[[Alberta Order of Excellence]] (2010)}}\n}}\n\n'''Robert Daniel Steadward''', {{post-nominals|list=[[Order of Canada|OC]], [[Alberta Order of Excellence|AOE]]}} (born May 26, 1946) is a [[Canada|Canadian]] sports administrator, professor, sports scientist, and author. Steadward helped organize the first Canadian wheelchair sport national championships in 1968, and later coached Canada in [[wheelchair basketball]] at the [[Summer Paralympics]]. He became a professor at the [[University of Alberta]] in 1971, later served as chairman of the Department of Athletics, and published more than 150 papers about disability sport. He was the founding president of the Alberta Wheelchair Sports Association in 1971, founded the Research and Training Centre for Athletes with Disabilities in 1978, served as president of the [[Canadian Paralympic Committee]] from 1984 to 1990, and later became a member of the [[Canadian Olympic Committee]].\n\nSteadward became the first president of the [[International Paralympic Committee]] (IPC) in 1989, after a successful campaign to consolidate international disability sport organizations. He signed a memorandum of understanding with [[Juan Antonio Samaranch]] of the [[International Olympic Committee]] during the [[2000 Summer Olympics]] which united the Paralympic movement with the [[Olympic Games]] movement, and saw one city host both events. During his tenure as president of the IPC, the organization grew from 37 to 172 national federations, and the [[Paralympic Games]] grew in popularity. The [[Commonwealth Games]] subsequently integrated disabled sports into its program, as a result of his efforts. His career has been recognized with the [[Order of Canada]], the [[Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal]], and the [[Alberta Order of Excellence]]. He has also been inducted into the [[Alberta Sports Hall of Fame]], the [[Canadian Disability Hall of Fame]], and [[Canada's Sports Hall of Fame]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nSteadward was born on born May 26, 1946, in [[Eston, Saskatchewan]].<ref name=\"LGofA\">{{cite web |title=Robert D. Steadward OC, PhD, LLD (Hon) |url=https://www.lieutenantgovernor.ab.ca/aoe/athletics/robert-d-steadward/index.html |year=2010 |publisher=Lieutenant Governor of Alberta |accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"sportshall\">{{cite web |title=Dr. Robert Steadward |url=https://www.sportshall.ca/hall-of-famers/hall-of-famers-search.html?proID=493&catID=all&lang=EN |website=Canada's Sports Hall of Fame |year=2007 |accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Peterson\">{{cite web |title=Robert Daniel Steadward |last= Peterson |first=Cynthia J. |date=December 17, 2007 |url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/robert-daniel-steadward |website=The Canadian Encyclopedia |accessdate=February 21, 2020}}</ref> His parents Danny and Irene ecouraged their children to be active participants in the community. As a youth, he enjoyed ice hockey, baseball, track and field, and riding horses.<ref name=\"LGofA\" /> He graduated from [[Luther College (Saskatchewan)|Luther College High School]] in [[Regina, Saskatchewan]] in 1964.<ref name=\"Luther\">{{cite web |title=Founder of Paralympic Movement |url=https://www.luthercollege.edu/high-school/alumni-friends/alumni/the-luther-story/fall-2018-alumni-profiles/bob-steadward-hs64 |publisher=Luther College |accessdate=February 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSteadward initially studied dentistry at the [[University of Alberta]] but abandoned that career path. After a few years of not attending school, he returned to the University of Alberta and earned a [[Bachelor of Physical Education]] in 1967.<ref name=\"LGofA\" /> While working as an intern with disabled athletes, he chose to volunteer in Paralympic sport and work with its athletes.<ref name=\"Luther\" /> He completed a [[Master's degree]] in [[physical education]] science and then a [[Doctorate]] at the [[University of Oregon]],<ref name=\"LGofA\" /><ref name=\"Peterson\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Faculty & Staff: Professor Emeritus |url=https://www.ualberta.ca/kinesiology-sport-recreation/about-us/faculty-staff/professor-emeritus |publisher=University of Alberta |accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref> during which he was a member of the Epsilon-Alpha chapter in the [[Kappa Sigma]] fraternity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kappasigma.org/alumni/sports|title=Kappa Sigma Famous Alumni: Sports|publisher=Kappa Sigma Fraternity|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929033343/http://www.kappasigma.org/alumni/sports|archivedate=September 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Canadian disabled sports==\n[[File:Australia - Canada, women's wheelchair basketball at Paralympics 2012 - 3.jpg|thumb|Steadward was president of the Canadian Paralympic Committee, which included national teams for [[wheelchair basketball]].|alt=Photo of Canada women's wheelchair basketball team in action]]\n\nSteadward became involved in disabled sports in Edmonton during the 1960s while he was a student. He coached a [[wheelchair basketball]] club called the Edmonton Handicaddies; and along with Gary McPherson, he helped organize the first Canadian wheelchair sport national championships, hosted at the University of Alberta in 1968.<ref name=\"Peterson\" /><ref name=\"MacKinnon\">{{cite news |title=Bob the builder enters Hall |url=https://www.pressreader.com/canada/edmonton-journal/20071022/282144991983432 |publisher=Edmonton Journal |date=October 22, 2007 |last=MacKinnon |first=John |accessdate=February 21, 2020}}</ref> After realizing there was lack of funds allocated to disabled sports, he decided to become more involved.<ref name=\"MacKinnon\" /> He coached for the [[Canadian Paralympic Committee]] (CPC) from 1966 to 1976, in swimming, wheelchair basketball, and track and field. He served as a national governor for the CPC from 1970 to 1986, was its treasurer from 1974 to 176, and was [[head of mission]] for international events from 1971 to 1980.<ref name=\"CPC-HOF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.ca/en/About-Us/Robert-Steadward-builder.html|title=Robert Steadward, Builder|year=2000|website=Canadian Paralympic Committee|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091225193054/http://www.paralympic.ca/en/About-Us/Robert-Steadward-builder.html|access-date=February 21, 2020|archive-date=December 25, 2009}}</ref> He founded the Alberta Wheelchair Sports Association in 1971, and served as its president until 1975.<ref name=\"CPC-HOF\" /> Before the association was founded, Steadward noted that activities for the disabled were managed by hospitals and long-term care facilities, and he wanted to see people in physiotherapy programs become involved in sports.<ref name=\"Naylor\">{{cite news |last1=Naylor |first1=David |title=Steadward leaves mark on Paralympic sports |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/steadward-leaves-mark-on-paralympic-sports/article25452293/ |accessdate=February 18, 2020 |work=The Globe and Mail |date=December 27, 2001 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219044824/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/steadward-leaves-mark-on-paralympic-sports/article25452293/ |archivedate=February 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1971, Steadward joined the Faculty of Kinesiology at the University of Alberta.<ref name=\"MacKinnon\" /> He helped design and construct a three-wheeled racing wheelchair used by [[Doug Bovee]] at the [[1972 Summer Paralympics]]. The experiment impacted the design of future racing wheelchairs, and opened the door for high-performance competition in disability sport.<ref name=\"MacKinnon\" /> Steadward coached the Canadian national wheelchair basketball team at the same Summer Paralympics, and at the 1973 [[IWAS World Games|International Stoke Mandeville Games]]. He was head of mission for Canada at the [[1976 Summer Paralympics]] in Toronto, and served as president of the Canadian Federation of Sport Organizations for the Disabled.<ref name=\"Peterson\" />\n\nSteadward founded the Research and Training Centre for Athletes with Disabilities in 1978.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Steadward Centre's 40th Anniversary Gala |url=https://www.ami.ca/Steadward |website=Accessible Media Inc. |accessdate=February 20, 2020 |date=May 28, 2018}}</ref> He envisioned a place where disabled athletes had a place to train for competition in sports, and have access to quality coaching.<ref name=\"Naylor\" /> He also founded the Canadian Sports Fund for the Physically Disabled in 1979, to provide funds for research, and was its chairman for 10 years.<ref name=\"LGofA\" /><ref name=\"CPC-HOF\" /> He also served as president of the Alberta Universities Athletic Association, chairman of Accreditation for the [[1978 Commonwealth Games]] hosted in Edmonton, and vice-president of the [[1983 Summer Universiade]] also hosted in Edmonton.<ref name=\"LGofA\" />\n\nSteadward served as president of the CPC from 1984 to 1990.<ref name=\"CPC-presidents\">{{cite web|url=http://paralympic.ca/past-presidents|title=Past Presidents|year=2017|website=Canadian Paralympic Committee|access-date=February 19, 2020}}</ref> While with the CPC, he also acted as a governor, treasurer, coach at the national level, and [[head of mission]] to international events.<ref name=\"LGofA\" /><ref name=\"CPC-presidents\" />\n\nSteadward retired from teaching at the University of Alberta in 2001. He had served as Associate Dean of the Faculty of Physical Education, and also chairman of the Department of Athletics. During his tenure, he worked with 50 graduate students working to improve disability sport.<ref name=\"LGofA\" /> His research led to more than 150 papers published about disability sport.<ref name=\"sportshall\" />\n\n==International disabled sports==\n[[File:201000 - Opening Ceremony swimmer Brendan Burkett flag - 3b - 2000 Sydney opening ceremony photo.jpg|right|thumb|250x250px|Robert Steadward ''(right rear)'' looks on as the Australian flag is brought to the stage by flagbearer Brendan Burkett during the opening ceremony of the 2000 Sydney Paralympic Games.]]\n\nSteadward campaigned to other global disability sport organizations to unite as one.<ref name=\"LGofA\" /> In the 1980s, Paralympic Games were organized as a joint venture by the [[International Wheelchair and Amputee Sports Federation|International Sport Organization for the Disabled]], the International Stoke Mandeville Games Federation, the [[International Blind Sports Federation]], and the [[Cerebral Palsy International Sports and Recreation Association]].<ref name=\"Peterson\" /> By 1987, he proposed creating a Paralympic sport model which eventually led to the creation of the [[International Paralympic Committee]] (IPC).<ref name=\"sportshall\" /><ref name=\"MacKinnon\" /> He was elected the first president of the IPC in 1989, and served in the role until 2001.<ref name=\"sportshall\" /><ref name=\"CPC-presidents\" /><ref>{{cite web |last1=Heidenreich |first1=Paul |title=Edmonton's champion for athletes with disabilities hopes for return of stolen Olympic, Paralympic medals |date=May 13, 2017 |work=Global News |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/3448909/edmontons-champion-for-athletes-with-disabilities-hopes-for-return-of-stolen-olympic-paralympic-medals/ |accessdate=February 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSteadward was elected to the [[International Olympic Committee]] (IOC) in 2000.<ref name=\"Peterson\" /><ref name=\"Naylor\" /> He served as co-chairman of the bid committee for the [[2001 World Championships in Athletics]] hosted in Edmonton.<ref name=\"LGofA\" /> He signed a memorandum of understanding with [[Juan Antonio Samaranch]] of the IOC during the [[2000 Summer Olympics]] which united the Paralympic movement with the [[Olympic Games]] movement, and saw one city host both events.<ref name=\"LGofA\" /><ref name=\"MacKinnon\" /> Steadward felt that being aligned with the Olympics would allow the Paralympics to reach its potential, but noted that the relationship was delicate at first \"because we're seen as the poor cousin needing help and we don't want that\".<ref name=\"Naylor\" /> He originally lobbied for full integration with Olympics, but decided the Paralympics would be stronger as a separate event.<ref name=\"Naylor\" />\n\n{{quote box|title=Foundation of the IPC... |quote=\"We had to move towards excellence and elite Paralympic sport. I'm proud that I was able to change attitudes by sending out these proposals around the world which said we can no longer treat our athletes like patients.\"|source=\u2014''Robert Steadward'', 2001<ref name=\"Naylor\" />|width=25%|align=right}}\n\nAfter serving the maximum of three terms as president of the IPC, Steadward was succeeded by [[Philip Craven]] in 2001.<ref name=\"Naylor\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=International Paralympic Committee Elects New President |url=https://www.sportcal.com/News/PressReleases/45230?&f=i%3A2%2FDirectory%7C%24s%3A1%2FOlympics%7C |website=sportcal.com |accessdate=February 18, 2020 |date=December 10, 2001}}</ref> The IPC was composed of 37 national federations in 1989. At the time of his retirement, the Paralympic Games had 172 nations involved and more than one million spectators in attendance.<ref name=\"Peterson\" /><ref name=\"Naylor\" /> In 2002, the [[Commonwealth Games]] integrated disabled sports into its program, as a result of Steadwards's efforts.<ref name=\"Peterson\" />\n\n==Later career==\nSteadward served on several sub-committees within the IOC which included, the Olympic Truce Foundation, environment and reforms, and the co-ordinating group for the [[2008 Summer Olympics]]. On behalf of the [[Canadian Olympic Committee]] and the CPC, he was a board member of the bid committee to host the [[2010 Winter Olympics]] and the [[2010 Winter Paralympics]] in Vancouver. He also served as board member for the 2005 [[World Masters Games]] hosted in Edmonton.<ref name=\"LGofA\" />\n\nSteadward has also worked as an agent for international athletes and country musicians.<ref name=\"LGofA\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Beverley |title=Agent defends his action |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/agent-defends-his-action/article25297809/ |accessdate=February 18, 2020 |work=The Globe and Mail |date=May 29, 2002}}</ref> He was an agent for gold medal Olympians [[Jamie Sal\u00e9]] and [[David Pelletier]] during their [[2001 Four Continents Figure Skating Championships]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jones |first1=Terry |title=Sale and Pelletier's marriage iced |url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/FigureSkating/2010/06/04/14269551.html |website=Canoe |accessdate=February 18, 2020 |date=June 4, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\nList of select publications by Steadward:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.worldcat.org/identities/lccn-n87126637/|title=Steadward, R. D. |website=[[WorldCat]]|access-date=February 21, 2020}}</ref>\n* ''Wheelchair sports classification system'' (1978)\n* ''Paralympics'' (1997)\n* ''Adapted physical activity'' (2000)\n\n==Personal life==\nSteadward married Laura Thompson in 1967, whom he met while studying at the University of Alberta.<ref name=\"LGofA\" /> The couple later had two daughters.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=bob_drbob|number=766776750948835328|date=August 19, 2016|title=Enjoying a drink with my daughters in Vancouver.}}</ref> He is a fan of the [[rodeo]], and has served as president of the River City Roundup Festival, Miss Rodeo Canada, and Friends of Pro Rodeo.<ref name=\"LGofA\" /> He resides in [[Edmonton]].<ref name=\"AOE\">{{cite web |title=Alberta's top citizens chosen to receive province's highest honour |url=https://www.alberta.ca/release.cfm?xID=28160166411A8-CC31-FF8B-FBD35889EE5584D6 |website=alberta.ca |accessdate=February 18, 2020 |date=April 19, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Honours and awards==\n[[File:Jubilee 2002 Medal Canada reverse.jpg|thumb|upright=0.7|Canadian version of the Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal|alt=Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal]]\n\nSteadward was inducted into the [[Alberta Sports Hall of Fame]] in 1984. In 1995, he received the Robert Jackson Award and the [[King Clancy]] Award.<ref name=\"sportshall\" /> The King Clancy Award recognizes contributions to Canadians with disabilities.<ref name=\"LGofA\"/> In 1996, he was inducted into the Edmonton Sports Hall of Fame, and became the namesake of the Dr. Robert D. Steadward Award. In 1997, he received the University of Alberta Rutherford Award.<ref name=\"sportshall\" /> The Rutherford Award recognizes outstanding teaching to undergraduates.<ref name=\"LGofA\"/>\n\nIn 1999, he was appointed [[Officer of the Order of Canada]].<ref name=\"sportshall\" /><ref name=\"CPC-HOF\" /> He was inducted into the Canadian Paralympic Hall of Fame in 2000.<ref name=\"CPC-HOF\" /> In 2001, he was made an honorary life president of the International Paralympic Committee,<ref name=\"sportshall\" /> and named Professor [[Emeritus]] at the University of Alberta.<ref name=\"LGofA\" /> In 2002, he was inducted into the [[Canadian Disability Hall of Fame]] and he received the [[Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal]].<ref name=\"sportshall\" /><ref name=\"CPC-HOF\" /> In 2005, he was named Albertan of the Century in Sport.<ref name=\"Peterson\" /> In 2007, he was inducted into [[Canada's Sports Hall of Fame]] in the builder category.<ref name=\"sportshall\" /><ref name=\"MacKinnon\" /> In 2010, he was appointed to the [[Alberta Order of Excellence]],<ref name=\"AOE\" /> and received the President's Award from the Canadian Sport Tourism Alliance.<ref name=\"Peterson\" />\n\nSteadward is an honorary life member of the Paralympic Sports Association, the Alberta Wheelchair Sports Association, the Canadian Wheelchair Sports Association, and the Canadian Paralympic Committee.<ref name=\"CPC-HOF\" /> Other sports and service honours include; member of the International Olympic Order, member of the International Paralympic Order, honorary life member of the Canadian Olympic Committee, the [[Lois Hole]] Community Development Award, and induction into the University of Alberta Sports Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"LGofA\"/>\n\nOther academic honours include; the University of Alberta Alumni of Distinction, honorary degrees from the University of Alberta and [[Universit\u00e9 catholique de Louvain]], and an honorary diploma from [[MacEwan University]].<ref name=\"LGofA\"/><ref name=\"sportshall\" />\n\n==Legacy==\nSteadward is known in Edmonton as \"Bob the Builder\".<ref name=\"MacKinnon\" /> The Research and Training Centre for Athletes with Disabilities he founded in 1978, was later known as the [[Rick Hansen]] Centre after the conclusion of the Man in Motion Tour.<ref name=\"Peterson\" /> It was rededicated as the Steadward Centre for Personal and Physical Achievement in 2000.<ref name=\"sportshall\" />\n\nThe [[Lieutenant Governor of Alberta]] credited Steadward for bringing attention to the Paralympic movement, and stated that he \"served to inspire all people with disability to pursue more active lifestyles\". The Steadward Centre for Personal and Physical Achievement which he founded was credited for being a \"model for independence and fitness training for people with disability\".<ref name=\"LGofA\"/> Canada's Sports Hall of Fame credited Steadward for promoting disability sport internationally, and \"giving the Paralympics an unprecedented level of support, respect and funding\".<ref name=\"sportshall\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Presidents of the International Paralympic Committee}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Steadward, Robert}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alberta Sports Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Canada's Sports Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Canadian Disability Hall of Fame]]\n[[Category:Canadian Paralympic Committee presidents]]\n[[Category:Canadian sports agents]]\n[[Category:Canadian sports builders]]\n[[Category:Canadian sports executives and administrators]]\n[[Category:International Olympic Committee members]]\n[[Category:International Paralympic Committee members]]\n[[Category:Luther College (Saskatchewan) alumni]]\n[[Category:Members of the Alberta Order of Excellence]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of Canada]]\n[[Category:Paralympic coaches of Canada]]\n[[Category:People from Eston, Saskatchewan]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the International Paralympic Committee]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Paralympic Order]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Edmonton]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Edmonton]]\n[[Category:University of Alberta alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Alberta faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Oregon alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Edmonton]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Canadian sports administrator}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| name        = Robert Steadward\n| image       = Robert Steadward IFAPA Inaugural Steadward Talks.jpg\n| caption     = Steadward at the IFAPA Inaugural Steadward Talks in 2019\n| honorific-suffix = [[Order of Canada|OC]] [[Alberta Order of Excellence|AOE]]\n| office      = 1st President of the [[International Paralympic Committee]]\n| term_start  = 1989\n| term_end    = 2001\n| successor   = [[Philip Craven]]\n| birth_date  = {{birth date and age|mf=yes|1946|5|26}}\n| birth_place = [[Eston, Saskatchewan]], Canada\n| nationality = Canadian\n| education   = [[Bachelor of Physical Education|BPhEd]], Master's, PhD\n| alma_mater  = [[University of Alberta]]<br>[[University of Oregon]]\n| occupation  = Sports administrator, professor, sports scientist, author\n| known_for   = [[Canadian Paralympic Committee]], [[International Paralympic Committee]]\n| awards      = {{hlist|[[Alberta Sports Hall of Fame]] (1984)|[[Order of Canada]] (1999)|[[Canadian Disability Hall of Fame]] (2002)|[[Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal]] 2002)|[[Canada's Sports Hall of Fame]] (2007)|[[Alberta Order of Excellence]] (2010)}}\n}}\n\n'''Robert Daniel Steadward''', {{post-nominals|list=[[Order of Canada|OC]], [[Alberta Order of Excellence|AOE]]}} (born May 26, 1946) is a [[Canada|Canadian]] retired sports administrator, professor, sports scientist, and author. Steadward helped organize the first Canadian wheelchair sport national championships in 1968, and later coached Canada in [[wheelchair basketball]] at the [[Summer Paralympics]]. He became a professor at the [[University of Alberta]] in 1971, later served as chairman of the Department of Athletics, and published more than 150 papers about disability sport. He was the founding president of the Alberta Wheelchair Sports Association in 1971, founded the Research and Training Centre for Athletes with Disabilities in 1978, served as president of the [[Canadian Paralympic Committee]] from 1984 to 1990, and later became a member of the [[Canadian Olympic Committee]].\n\nSteadward became the first president of the [[International Paralympic Committee]] (IPC) in 1989, after a successful campaign to consolidate international disability sport organizations. He signed a memorandum of understanding with [[Juan Antonio Samaranch]] of the [[International Olympic Committee]] during the [[2000 Summer Olympics]] which united the Paralympic movement with the [[Olympic Games]] movement, and saw one city host both events. During his tenure as president of the IPC, the organization grew from 37 to 172 national federations, and the [[Paralympic Games]] grew in popularity. The [[Commonwealth Games]] subsequently integrated disabled sports into its program, as a result of his efforts. His career has been recognized with the [[Order of Canada]], the [[Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal]], and the [[Alberta Order of Excellence]]. He has also been inducted into the [[Alberta Sports Hall of Fame]], the [[Canadian Disability Hall of Fame]], and [[Canada's Sports Hall of Fame]].\n\n==Early life and education==\nSteadward was born on born May 26, 1946, in [[Eston, Saskatchewan]].<ref name=\"LGofA\">{{cite web |title=Robert D. Steadward OC, PhD, LLD (Hon) |url=https://www.lieutenantgovernor.ab.ca/aoe/athletics/robert-d-steadward/index.html |year=2010 |publisher=Lieutenant Governor of Alberta |accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"sportshall\">{{cite web |title=Dr. Robert Steadward |url=https://www.sportshall.ca/hall-of-famers/hall-of-famers-search.html?proID=493&catID=all&lang=EN |website=Canada's Sports Hall of Fame |year=2007 |accessdate=February 19, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Peterson\">{{cite web |title=Robert Daniel Steadward |last= Peterson |first=Cynthia J. |date=December 17, 2007 |url=https://www.thecanadianencyclopedia.ca/en/article/robert-daniel-steadward |website=The Canadian Encyclopedia |accessdate=February 21, 2020}}</ref> His parents Danny and Irene ecouraged their children to be active participants in the community. As a youth, he enjoyed ice hockey, baseball, track and field, and riding horses.<ref name=\"LGofA\" /> He graduated from [[Luther College (Saskatchewan)|Luther College High School]] in [[Regina, Saskatchewan]] in 1964.<ref name=\"Luther\">{{cite web |title=Founder of Paralympic Movement |url=https://www.luthercollege.edu/high-school/alumni-friends/alumni/the-luther-story/fall-2018-alumni-profiles/bob-steadward-hs64 |publisher=Luther College |accessdate=February 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSteadward initially studied dentistry at the [[University of Alberta]] but abandoned that career path. After a few years of not attending school, he returned to the University of Alberta and earned a [[Bachelor of Physical Education]] in 1967.<ref name=\"LGofA\" /> While working as an intern with disabled athletes, he chose to volunteer in Paralympic sport and work with its athletes.<ref name=\"Luther\" /> He completed a [[Master's degree]] in [[physical education]] science and then a [[Doctorate]] at the [[University of Oregon]],<ref name=\"LGofA\" /><ref name=\"Peterson\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=Faculty & Staff: Professor Emeritus |url=https://www.ualberta.ca/kinesiology-sport-recreation/about-us/faculty-staff/professor-emeritus |publisher=University of Alberta |accessdate=February 20, 2020}}</ref> during which he was a member of the Epsilon-Alpha chapter in the [[Kappa Sigma]] fraternity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kappasigma.org/alumni/sports|title=Kappa Sigma Famous Alumni: Sports|publisher=Kappa Sigma Fraternity|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110929033343/http://www.kappasigma.org/alumni/sports|archivedate=September 29, 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Canadian disabled sports==\n[[File:Australia - Canada, women's wheelchair basketball at Paralympics 2012 - 3.jpg|thumb|Steadward was president of the Canadian Paralympic Committee, which included national teams for [[wheelchair basketball]].|alt=Photo of Canada women's wheelchair basketball team in action]]\n\nSteadward became involved in disabled sports in Edmonton during the 1960s while he was a student. He coached a [[wheelchair basketball]] club called the Edmonton Handicaddies; and along with Gary McPherson, he helped organize the first Canadian wheelchair sport national championships, hosted at the University of Alberta in 1968.<ref name=\"Peterson\" /><ref name=\"MacKinnon\">{{cite news |title=Bob the builder enters Hall |url=https://www.pressreader.com/canada/edmonton-journal/20071022/282144991983432 |publisher=Edmonton Journal |date=October 22, 2007 |last=MacKinnon |first=John |accessdate=February 21, 2020}}</ref> After realizing there was lack of funds allocated to disabled sports, he decided to become more involved.<ref name=\"MacKinnon\" /> He coached for the [[Canadian Paralympic Committee]] (CPC) from 1966 to 1976, in swimming, wheelchair basketball, and track and field. He served as a national governor for the CPC from 1970 to 1986, was its treasurer from 1974 to 176, and was [[head of mission]] for international events from 1971 to 1980.<ref name=\"CPC-HOF\">{{cite web|url=http://www.paralympic.ca/en/About-Us/Robert-Steadward-builder.html|title=Robert Steadward, Builder|year=2000|website=Canadian Paralympic Committee|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091225193054/http://www.paralympic.ca/en/About-Us/Robert-Steadward-builder.html|access-date=February 21, 2020|archive-date=December 25, 2009}}</ref> He founded the Alberta Wheelchair Sports Association in 1971, and served as its president until 1975.<ref name=\"CPC-HOF\" /> Before the association was founded, Steadward noted that activities for the disabled were managed by hospitals and long-term care facilities, and he wanted to see people in physiotherapy programs become involved in sports.<ref name=\"Naylor\">{{cite news |last1=Naylor |first1=David |title=Steadward leaves mark on Paralympic sports |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/steadward-leaves-mark-on-paralympic-sports/article25452293/ |accessdate=February 18, 2020 |work=The Globe and Mail |date=December 27, 2001 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20200219044824/https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/steadward-leaves-mark-on-paralympic-sports/article25452293/ |archivedate=February 18, 2020}}</ref>\n\nIn 1971, Steadward joined the Faculty of Kinesiology at the University of Alberta.<ref name=\"MacKinnon\" /> He helped design and construct a three-wheeled racing wheelchair used by [[Doug Bovee]] at the [[1972 Summer Paralympics]]. The experiment impacted the design of future racing wheelchairs, and opened the door for high-performance competition in disability sport.<ref name=\"MacKinnon\" /> Steadward coached the Canadian national wheelchair basketball team at the same Summer Paralympics, and at the 1973 [[IWAS World Games|International Stoke Mandeville Games]]. He was head of mission for Canada at the [[1976 Summer Paralympics]] in Toronto, and served as president of the Canadian Federation of Sport Organizations for the Disabled.<ref name=\"Peterson\" />\n\nSteadward founded the Research and Training Centre for Athletes with Disabilities in 1978.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Steadward Centre's 40th Anniversary Gala |url=https://www.ami.ca/Steadward |website=Accessible Media Inc. |accessdate=February 20, 2020 |date=May 28, 2018}}</ref> He envisioned a place where disabled athletes had a place to train for competition in sports, and have access to quality coaching.<ref name=\"Naylor\" /> He also founded the Canadian Sports Fund for the Physically Disabled in 1979, to provide funds for research, and was its chairman for 10 years.<ref name=\"LGofA\" /><ref name=\"CPC-HOF\" /> He also served as president of the Alberta Universities Athletic Association, chairman of Accreditation for the [[1978 Commonwealth Games]] hosted in Edmonton, and vice-president of the [[1983 Summer Universiade]] also hosted in Edmonton.<ref name=\"LGofA\" />\n\nSteadward served as president of the CPC from 1984 to 1990.<ref name=\"CPC-presidents\">{{cite web|url=http://paralympic.ca/past-presidents|title=Past Presidents|year=2017|website=Canadian Paralympic Committee|access-date=February 19, 2020}}</ref> While with the CPC, he also acted as a governor, treasurer, coach at the national level, and [[head of mission]] to international events.<ref name=\"LGofA\" /><ref name=\"CPC-presidents\" />\n\nSteadward retired from teaching at the University of Alberta in 2001. He had served as Associate Dean of the Faculty of Physical Education, and also chairman of the Department of Athletics. During his tenure, he worked with 50 graduate students working to improve disability sport.<ref name=\"LGofA\" /> His research led to more than 150 papers published about disability sport.<ref name=\"sportshall\" />\n\n==International disabled sports==\n[[File:201000 - Opening Ceremony swimmer Brendan Burkett flag - 3b - 2000 Sydney opening ceremony photo.jpg|right|thumb|250x250px|Robert Steadward ''(right rear)'' looks on as the Australian flag is brought to the stage by flagbearer Brendan Burkett during the opening ceremony of the 2000 Sydney Paralympic Games.]]\n\nSteadward campaigned to other global disability sport organizations to unite as one.<ref name=\"LGofA\" /> In the 1980s, Paralympic Games were organized as a joint venture by the [[International Wheelchair and Amputee Sports Federation|International Sport Organization for the Disabled]], the International Stoke Mandeville Games Federation, the [[International Blind Sports Federation]], and the [[Cerebral Palsy International Sports and Recreation Association]].<ref name=\"Peterson\" /> By 1987, he proposed creating a Paralympic sport model which eventually led to the creation of the [[International Paralympic Committee]] (IPC).<ref name=\"sportshall\" /><ref name=\"MacKinnon\" /> He was elected the first president of the IPC in 1989, and served in the role until 2001.<ref name=\"sportshall\" /><ref name=\"CPC-presidents\" /><ref>{{cite web |last1=Heidenreich |first1=Paul |title=Edmonton's champion for athletes with disabilities hopes for return of stolen Olympic, Paralympic medals |date=May 13, 2017 |work=Global News |url=https://globalnews.ca/news/3448909/edmontons-champion-for-athletes-with-disabilities-hopes-for-return-of-stolen-olympic-paralympic-medals/ |accessdate=February 21, 2020}}</ref>\n\nSteadward was elected to the [[International Olympic Committee]] (IOC) in 2000.<ref name=\"Peterson\" /><ref name=\"Naylor\" /> He served as co-chairman of the bid committee for the [[2001 World Championships in Athletics]] hosted in Edmonton.<ref name=\"LGofA\" /> He signed a memorandum of understanding with [[Juan Antonio Samaranch]] of the IOC during the [[2000 Summer Olympics]] which united the Paralympic movement with the [[Olympic Games]] movement, and saw one city host both events.<ref name=\"LGofA\" /><ref name=\"MacKinnon\" /> Steadward felt that being aligned with the Olympics would allow the Paralympics to reach its potential, but noted that the relationship was delicate at first \"because we're seen as the poor cousin needing help and we don't want that\".<ref name=\"Naylor\" /> He originally lobbied for full integration with Olympics, but decided the Paralympics would be stronger as a separate event.<ref name=\"Naylor\" />\n\n{{quote box|title=Foundation of the IPC... |quote=\"We had to move towards excellence and elite Paralympic sport. I'm proud that I was able to change attitudes by sending out these proposals around the world which said we can no longer treat our athletes like patients.\"|source=\u2014''Robert Steadward'', 2001<ref name=\"Naylor\" />|width=25%|align=right}}\n\nAfter serving the maximum of three terms as president of the IPC, Steadward was succeeded by [[Philip Craven]] in 2001.<ref name=\"Naylor\" /><ref>{{cite web |title=International Paralympic Committee Elects New President |url=https://www.sportcal.com/News/PressReleases/45230?&f=i%3A2%2FDirectory%7C%24s%3A1%2FOlympics%7C |website=sportcal.com |accessdate=February 18, 2020 |date=December 10, 2001}}</ref> The IPC was composed of 37 national federations in 1989. At the time of his retirement, the Paralympic Games had 172 nations involved and more than one million spectators in attendance.<ref name=\"Peterson\" /><ref name=\"Naylor\" /> In 2002, the [[Commonwealth Games]] integrated disabled sports into its program, as a result of Steadwards's efforts.<ref name=\"Peterson\" />\n\n==Later career==\nSteadward served on several sub-committees within the IOC which included, the Olympic Truce Foundation, environment and reforms, and the co-ordinating group for the [[2008 Summer Olympics]]. On behalf of the [[Canadian Olympic Committee]] and the CPC, he was a board member of the bid committee to host the [[2010 Winter Olympics]] and the [[2010 Winter Paralympics]] in Vancouver. He also served as board member for the 2005 [[World Masters Games]] hosted in Edmonton.<ref name=\"LGofA\" />\n\nSteadward has also worked as an agent for international athletes and country musicians.<ref name=\"LGofA\" /><ref>{{cite news |last1=Smith |first1=Beverley |title=Agent defends his action |url=https://www.theglobeandmail.com/sports/agent-defends-his-action/article25297809/ |accessdate=February 18, 2020 |work=The Globe and Mail |date=May 29, 2002}}</ref> He was an agent for gold medal Olympians [[Jamie Sal\u00e9]] and [[David Pelletier]] during their [[2001 Four Continents Figure Skating Championships]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Jones |first1=Terry |title=Sale and Pelletier's marriage iced |url=http://slam.canoe.com/Slam/FigureSkating/2010/06/04/14269551.html |website=Canoe |accessdate=February 18, 2020 |date=June 4, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Publications==\nList of select publications by Steadward:<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.worldcat.org/identities/lccn-n87126637/|title=Steadward, R. D. |website=[[WorldCat]]|access-date=February 21, 2020}}</ref>\n* ''Wheelchair sports classification system'' (1978)\n* ''Paralympics'' (1997)\n* ''Adapted physical activity'' (2000)\n\n==Personal life==\nSteadward married Laura Thompson in 1967, whom he met while studying at the University of Alberta.<ref name=\"LGofA\" /> The couple later had two daughters.<ref>{{cite tweet|user=bob_drbob|number=766776750948835328|date=August 19, 2016|title=Enjoying a drink with my daughters in Vancouver.}}</ref> He is a fan of the [[rodeo]], and has served as president of the River City Roundup Festival, Miss Rodeo Canada, and Friends of Pro Rodeo.<ref name=\"LGofA\" /> He resides in [[Edmonton]].<ref name=\"AOE\">{{cite web |title=Alberta's top citizens chosen to receive province's highest honour |url=https://www.alberta.ca/release.cfm?xID=28160166411A8-CC31-FF8B-FBD35889EE5584D6 |website=alberta.ca |accessdate=February 18, 2020 |date=April 19, 2010}}</ref>\n\n==Honours and awards==\n[[File:Jubilee 2002 Medal Canada reverse.jpg|thumb|upright=0.7|Canadian version of the Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal|alt=Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal]]\n\nSteadward was inducted into the [[Alberta Sports Hall of Fame]] in 1984. In 1995, he received the Robert Jackson Award and the [[King Clancy]] Award.<ref name=\"sportshall\" /> The King Clancy Award recognizes contributions to Canadians with disabilities.<ref name=\"LGofA\"/> In 1996, he was inducted into the Edmonton Sports Hall of Fame, and became the namesake of the Dr. Robert D. Steadward Award. In 1997, he received the University of Alberta Rutherford Award.<ref name=\"sportshall\" /> The Rutherford Award recognizes outstanding teaching to undergraduates.<ref name=\"LGofA\"/>\n\nIn 1999, he was appointed [[Officer of the Order of Canada]].<ref name=\"sportshall\" /><ref name=\"CPC-HOF\" /> He was inducted into the Canadian Paralympic Hall of Fame in 2000.<ref name=\"CPC-HOF\" /> In 2001, he was made an honorary life president of the International Paralympic Committee,<ref name=\"sportshall\" /> and named Professor [[Emeritus]] at the University of Alberta.<ref name=\"LGofA\" /> In 2002, he was inducted into the [[Canadian Disability Hall of Fame]] and he received the [[Queen Elizabeth II Golden Jubilee Medal]].<ref name=\"sportshall\" /><ref name=\"CPC-HOF\" /> In 2005, he was named Albertan of the Century in Sport.<ref name=\"Peterson\" /> In 2007, he was inducted into [[Canada's Sports Hall of Fame]] in the builder category.<ref name=\"sportshall\" /><ref name=\"MacKinnon\" /> In 2010, he was appointed to the [[Alberta Order of Excellence]],<ref name=\"AOE\" /> and received the President's Award from the Canadian Sport Tourism Alliance.<ref name=\"Peterson\" />\n\nSteadward is an honorary life member of the Paralympic Sports Association, the Alberta Wheelchair Sports Association, the Canadian Wheelchair Sports Association, and the Canadian Paralympic Committee.<ref name=\"CPC-HOF\" /> Other sports and service honours include; member of the International Olympic Order, member of the International Paralympic Order, honorary life member of the Canadian Olympic Committee, the [[Lois Hole]] Community Development Award, and induction into the University of Alberta Sports Hall of Fame.<ref name=\"LGofA\"/>\n\nOther academic honours include; the University of Alberta Alumni of Distinction, honorary degrees from the University of Alberta and [[Universit\u00e9 catholique de Louvain]], and an honorary diploma from [[MacEwan University]].<ref name=\"LGofA\"/><ref name=\"sportshall\" />\n\n==Legacy==\nSteadward is known in Edmonton as \"Bob the Builder\".<ref name=\"MacKinnon\" /> The Research and Training Centre for Athletes with Disabilities he founded in 1978, was later known as the [[Rick Hansen]] Centre after the conclusion of the Man in Motion Tour.<ref name=\"Peterson\" /> It was rededicated as the Steadward Centre for Personal and Physical Achievement in 2000.<ref name=\"sportshall\" />\n\nThe [[Lieutenant Governor of Alberta]] credited Steadward for bringing attention to the Paralympic movement, and stated that he \"served to inspire all people with disability to pursue more active lifestyles\". The Steadward Centre for Personal and Physical Achievement which he founded was credited for being a \"model for independence and fitness training for people with disability\".<ref name=\"LGofA\"/> Canada's Sports Hall of Fame credited Steadward for promoting disability sport internationally, and \"giving the Paralympics an unprecedented level of support, respect and funding\".<ref name=\"sportshall\" />\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Presidents of the International Paralympic Committee}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Steadward, Robert}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alberta Sports Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Canada's Sports Hall of Fame inductees]]\n[[Category:Canadian Disability Hall of Fame]]\n[[Category:Canadian Paralympic Committee presidents]]\n[[Category:Canadian sports agents]]\n[[Category:Canadian sports builders]]\n[[Category:Canadian sports executives and administrators]]\n[[Category:International Olympic Committee members]]\n[[Category:International Paralympic Committee members]]\n[[Category:Luther College (Saskatchewan) alumni]]\n[[Category:Members of the Alberta Order of Excellence]]\n[[Category:Officers of the Order of Canada]]\n[[Category:Paralympic coaches of Canada]]\n[[Category:People from Eston, Saskatchewan]]\n[[Category:Presidents of the International Paralympic Committee]]\n[[Category:Recipients of the Paralympic Order]]\n[[Category:Scientists from Edmonton]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Edmonton]]\n[[Category:University of Alberta alumni]]\n[[Category:University of Alberta faculty]]\n[[Category:University of Oregon alumni]]\n[[Category:Writers from Edmonton]]\n", "name_user": "183.171.100.86", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_Steadward"}
{"title_page": "USS Tucker (DD-374)", "text_new": "{{other ships|USS Tucker}}\n{{short description|Mahan-class destroyer}}\n{{coord missing|Pacific Ocean}}\n{{good article}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Uss Tucker DD-374.jpg\n|Ship caption=USS ''Tucker'' off the [[Norfolk Navy Yard]], [[Portsmouth, Virginia]], 2{{nbsp}}March 1937\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag={{USN flag|1942}}\n|Ship name=''Tucker''\n|Ship namesake=[[Samuel Tucker]]\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=[[Norfolk Navy Yard]]\n|Ship laid down=15 August 1934\n|Ship launched=26 February 1936\n|Ship commissioned=23 July 1936\n|Ship struck=2 December 1944\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship fate=Struck [[Naval mine|mine]] off [[Espiritu Santo]], [[New Hebrides]], 4{{nbsp}}August 1942\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=(as built)\n|Ship class={{sclass-|Mahan|destroyer}}\n|Ship displacement=*{{convert|1500|LT|t|0|lk=in}} ([[standard load]])\n*{{convert|1725|LT|t}} ([[deep load]])\n|Ship length={{convert|341|ft|m|abbr=on|1}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|35|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on|1}}\n|Ship draft={{convert|10|ft|7|in|m|abbr=on|1}}\n|Ship power=*{{convert|46,000|shp|lk=on}}\n*4 [[water-tube boiler]]s           \n|Ship propulsion=2 [[Propeller shaft|shafts]] 2 geared [[steam turbine]]s\n|Ship speed={{convert|37|kn|lk=in}}\n|Ship range={{convert|6940|nmi|lk=in|abbr=on}} at {{convert|12|kn}}\n|Ship complement=158 officers and enlisted men\n|Ship sensors=*1 \u00d7 [[gun director]] above bridge\n|Ship armament=*5 \u00d7 single [[5\"/38 caliber gun|{{convert|5|in|mm|abbr=on|0}}]] [[DP gun]]s\n*3 \u00d7 quadruple [[American 21 inch torpedo|21 in (533 mm)]] [[torpedo tube]]s\n*4 \u00d7 single [[M2 Browning|.50 cal (12.7 mm)]] AA machine guns\n*2 \u00d7 [[depth charge]] stern racks\n*Depth charge projectors (aka [[K-guns]])\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''USS ''Tucker'' (DD-374)''' was a {{sclass-|Mahan|destroyer}} of the [[United States Navy]] and was commissioned in 1936. ''Tucker''{{'}}s [[main battery]] consisted of five [[Dual-purpose gun|dual-purpose]] [[38 caliber 5-inch (127 mm) guns]].\n\nFirst assigned to the [[United States Battle Fleet]] in San Diego, California, ''Tucker'' operated along the [[West Coast of the United States|West Coast]] and in the [[Hawaiian Islands]]. After participating in [[naval exercise]]s in the [[Caribbean Sea]], she returned to duty in [[Territory of Hawaii|Hawaii]]. She then went on a goodwill tour to New Zealand, returning to Hawaii and docking at [[Pearl Harbor]]. When the [[Empire of Japan|Japanese]] [[Attack on Pearl Harbor|attacked Pearl Harbor]] on 7{{nbsp}}December 1941, ''Tucker'' was undergoing an overhaul but sustained no damage. Soon afterward, she  began escorting convoys between the West Coast and Hawaii. ''Tucker'' was then tasked with escort duty to islands in the [[South Pacific Ocean|Sourth Pacific]].\n\n''Tucker'' steamed out of port on 1 August 1942, escorting a cargo ship to [[Espiritu Santo]]. They entered its harbor on 4 August, where they had, unknowingly, moved into a [[minefield]] laid by the US Navy. ''Tucker'' struck at least one [[Naval mine|mine]] and was torn almost in two, killing three sailors. The rest of the crew survived but the destroyer sank. ''Tucker'' had not been informed of the minefield. \n\n==Design==\n\n===General characteristics===  \n''Tucker'' [[Displacement (ship)|displaced]] {{cvt|1500|LT|t|0|lk=on}}\nat [[standard load]] and {{convert|1725|LT|t}} at [[deep load]]. The ship's [[length overall|overall length]] was {{convert|341|ft|m|1}}, her [[beam (nautical)|beam]] was {{convert|35|ft|6|in|m|1}}, and her [[draft (hull)|draft]] was {{convert|10|ft|7|in|m|1}}. Her peace-time complement was 158 officers and enlisted men.{{sfn|Friedman|2004|pp=465\u2013466}}\n\nShe had a [[Tripod mast|tripod]] [[foremast]] and a pole mainmast. To improve the [[antiaircraft]] [[field of fire (weaponry)|field of fire]], her [[tripod]] foremast was constructed without nautical [[rigging]].{{sfn|Friedman|2004|p=88}} The destroyer was fitted with emergency [[diesel generators]], replacing the storage batteries of earlier destroyers. Gun crew shelters were also built fore and aft for the superimposed guns. A third set of quadruple [[torpedo tubes]] was added, with one mounted on the [[centerline]] and two in the side positions.{{sfn |Friedman|2004|p=88}}\n\n===Machinery and armament===\n''Tucker'' was fitted with four [[water-tube boiler]]s built by either [[Babcock & Wilcox]] or [[Foster Wheeler]]. They generated the steam that propelled the two [[General Electric]] geared [[steam turbine]]s, developing {{convert|46,000|shp|abbr=on|lk=on}} for a maximum speed of {{convert|37|kn|lk=in}}. ''Tucker'' carried a maximum of {{convert|523|LT|t}} of [[fuel oil]], with a trial range of {{convert|7300|nmi|lk=in}} at {{convert|12|kn|lk=in}}. The ship's\nwartime ranges were {{convert|6940|nmi|lk=in}} at {{convert|12|kn|lk=in}} and {{convert|4360|nmi|lk=in}} at {{convert|20|kn|lk=in}}.\nThe ship's design incorporated a new generation of land-based propulsion machinery. The boilers were capable of reaching {{convert|650\u2013700|F|C|sigfig=2}}, powering the high-pressure turbines with [[double reduction gearing|double reduction gears]] that enabled the turbines to run faster and more efficiently than in previous destroyer designs.{{sfn|Friedman|2004|p=88}}\n\n''Tucker''{{'}}s [[main battery]] consisted of five [[Dual-purpose gun|dual-purpose]] [[38 caliber 5-inch (127 mm) guns]], equipped with the MK{{nbsp}}33 gun [[fire-control system]].{{sfn|Friedman|2004|p=465}} Each gun was configured for surface and aerial targets.{{sfn |Friedman|2004| p=88}} The ship's antiaircraft battery had four water-cooled [[.50 caliber machine gun]]s (12.7&nbsp;mm).{{sfn|Hodges|Friedman|1979|p=111}} The ship was fitted with three quadruple torpedo-tube mounts for twelve {{convert|21|in|mm|adj=on|0}} [[torpedo]]es, guided by the Mark{{nbsp}}27 torpedo fire-control system.{{sfn|Friedman|2004|p=465}} She was rigged for two [[depth charge]] roll-off racks and for depth charge projectors (K-guns).{{sfn|Friedman|2004|p=86}} In early 1942, the Navy began to refit the ''Mahan''-class destroyers with new antiaircraft armament, although most of the class was not refitted until sometime in 1944.{{sfn|Hodges|Friedman|1979|p=145}}\n\n==Construction and service history==\n\n''Tucker'' was one of eighteen [[Mahan-class destroyer|Mahan-class destroyers]] and was built at the [[Norfolk Navy Yard]] in [[Portsmouth, Virginia]].{{sfn|Conway's|1980|pp=125\u2013126}} She was the second vessel to be named for [[Samuel Tucker]], who had been an officer in the [[Continental Navy]] and the United States Navy.{{sfn|Parkin|1996|p=67}} ''Tucker''{{'}}s [[keel]] was laid down on 15{{nbsp}}August 1934. She was [[Ceremonial ship launching|launched]] on 26{{nbsp}}February 1936 and [[Christening|christened]] by a third cousin of Tucker. The ship was commissioned in the United States Navy on 23{{nbsp}}July, with [[Lieutenant commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]] George T. Howard in command.{{sfn|Parkin|1996|p=68-69}}\n\n[[File:USS Tucker.jpg|thumb|alt=Naval warship rigged with sails|''Tucker'' rigged with sails, June 1940]]\nAfter her [[shakedown cruise]], she joined destroyer forces attached to the United States Battle Fleet in [[San Diego]], [[California]]. She operated with them along the West Coast and in the Hawaiian islands as part of Destroyer Squadron{{nbsp}}3 of the Destroyer Division.\nIn February 1939, she took part in [[Fleet Problem&nbsp;XX]], a naval exercise held in the Caribbean Sea and Atlantic Ocean and observed by President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]]. As tensions with Japan increased, the fleet was ordered to return to Hawaiian waters.{{sfn|NHHC}}\n\nIn June 1940, ''Tucker'' steamed from Hawaii to a location east of [[Wake Island]] for fleet exercises. In ''United States Navy Destroyers of World War II,'' John Reilly, Jr. described the uncommon method used to power the vessel on its return to Hawaii: {{blockquote|... Tucker stretched her fuel supply by rigging Sails. Her homemade [[foresail]] and [[mainsail]] moved Tucker at an estimated 3.4 knots, letting her maintain [[Glossary of nautical terms#steerageway|steerageway]] as she loitered on station several days.{{sfn|Reilly|1983|p=30}}}}\n\n''Tucker'' continued operating between Hawaii and the West Coast into February 1941. She then set course for New Zealand on a goodwill tour, arriving in [[Auckland]] on 17 March. Returning to Pearl Harbor, she took part in routine exercises at sea before returning to her homeport of San Diego on 19{{nbsp}}September. After a short stay, ''Tucker'' steamed to Hawaii in November as part of Task Force{{nbsp}}19, operating again in the Hawaiian Islands. Shortly afterward, she put into Pearl Harbor for an overhaul by a [[destroyer tender]].{{sfn|NHHC}}\n\nWhen the [[Empire of Japan|Japanese]] [[Attack on Pearl Harbor|attacked Pearl Harbor]] on 7 December 1941, ''Tucker'' was one of five destroyers moored at berth X\u20139, East Loch, alongside the destroyer tender {{USS|Whitney|AD-4|2}}.{{sfn|Roscoe|1953|pp=47\u201348}} Even before ''Tucker''{{'}}s [[general quarters]] alarm could be sounded, one of her on-deck sailors began firing a 50-caliber machine gun at the first wave of Japanese aircraft. When the second wave attacked, every ship that could opened fire. ''Tucker''{{'}}s gunners scored hits on at least two aircraft: one crashed in a cane field, another in flames disappeared over a mountaintop. Because ''Tucker'' was at Pearl Harbor for overhaul, much of her machinery had been torn down for repairs; despite the crew's efforts, they were unable to get the ship underway until that evening.{{sfn|Parkin|1996|p=68}}\n\nAfter her overhaul, ''Tucker'' patrolled off Pearl Harbor and spent several months escorting convoys between Hawaii and the West Coast. With new orders, she steamed to the South Pacific for convoy duty. ''Tucker'' then escorted the auxiliary ship {{USS|Wright|AV-1|2}} to [[Tutuila]], [[American Samoa]], as part of the drive to fortify outposts. She then escorted her charge to [[Suva]], [[British Fiji|Fiji]], and proceeded to [[Noumea]], [[New Caledonia]]. Steaming on for Australia, she arrived at [[Sydney]] on 27{{nbsp}}April. After taking on fuel, she visited [[Melbourne]], [[Perth, Western Australia|Perth]], and [[Fremantle, Western Australia|Fremantle]] before steaming back to Sydney. ''Tucker'' and  ''Wright'' returned to Suva, arriving on 3{{nbsp}}June 1942. For the remainder of June and into the first week of July, ''Tucker'' operated out of Suva before relieving the cruiser {{USS|Boise|CL-47|2}} of convoy escort duties on 10{{nbsp}}July. On{{nbsp}}30 July, the ship arrived at Auckland and the following day started back for Suva.{{sfn|NHHC}}\n\n==Fate==\n[[Image:DD-374 sunk 5Aug1942 EspirituSanto NAN09-10-86.jpg|thumb|alt=Naval ship struck by a mine and sinking|USS ''Tucker'' (D-374) sinking south of Espiritu Santo,  5 August 1942]]\n\nOn 1{{nbsp}}August 1942 ''Tucker'' left Suva, escorting the cargo ship SS ''Nira Luckenbach'' to [[Espiritu Santo]], [[New Hebrides]].{{sfn|NHHC}} On 4{{nbsp}}August ''Tucker'' led the cargo ship into the harbor at Espiritu Santo, as she headed into the western entrance, she struck at least one [[Naval mine|mine]]. The explosion tore her hull nearly in two at the [[Funnel (ship)|No.{{nbsp}}1 stack]], killing all three crew members on watch in the forward [[fire room]]. The rest of the ship's company survived.\n''Nira Luckenbach'' and other vessels rescued sailors from their sinking ship. ''Tucker''{{'}}s [[stern]] sank the following morning; a diving party scuttled and sank her [[bow (ship)|bow]].{{sfn|Roscoe|1953|p=165}} The ship had steamed into the [[Segond Channel]] unaware that the minelayers {{USS|Gamble|DD-123|2}}, {{USS|Breese|DD-122|2}}, and {{USS|Tracy|DD-214|2}} had laid mines at its western entrance. An investigation revealed that ''Tucker's'' captain had not been informed of the minefield.{{sfn|Rohwer|2005|p=184}} She was stricken from the ''[[Naval Vessel Register]]'' on 2{{nbsp}}December 1944.{{sfn|NHHC}} ''Tucker''{{'}}s loss was a setback to the [[United States Pacific Fleet|Pacific Fleet]], which was trying to assemble every available ship for the [[Battle of Guadalcanal]].{{sfn|Roscoe|1953|p=165}}\n\nThree days after ''Tucker'' sank, the seagoing tugboat {{USS|Navajo|AT-64|2}} arrived on site with divers, [[marine salvage|salvaging]] her guns, turbines, anchors and chains. During the remainder of the war, the Navy used the wreckage site for diver training; they did not undertake further salvaging. \nSettling in just {{convert|60|ft}} of water, the ship was easily accessible to private salvors, who harvested anything of value, ransacking and further scattering ''Tucker''{{'}}s remains. Sport divers also had a destructive effect on the site, which by 1997 resembled an \"underwater junkyard\".{{sfn|Stone|1997|pp=78\u201379}} Mike Gerken, an underwater photojournalist, dove the ''Tucker'' wreckage site several times; in 2013 he eulogized ''Tucker'' and other sunken ships:\n\n{{quote\n|text=To see a ship with a distinguished record as the ''Tucker'' in such a poor state gave me pause for thought. I pondered that wrecks, like the ''Tucker'', will gradually disappear and to be saddened by this inevitable fact would be pointless. What is important is that the memory of these ships be kept alive by telling their stories.\n|author=Mike Gerken\n|title=\"The USS ''Tucker'': A Prestigious Past with an Inglorious End\"\n|source=''Wreck Diving Magazine''{{sfn|Gerken|2013}}\n}}\n\n''Tucker'' and [[SS President Coolidge|SS ''President Coolidge'']], a troopship, suffered similar fates less than three months apart; both were sunk in different locations of the same U.S. Navy minefield, and both later became diving sites.{{sfn|Gerken|2013}}\n\n==Honors==\n''Tucker'' received one [[battle star]] for her [[World War II]] service.{{sfn|Parkin|1996|p=69}}\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{cite book|author=<nowiki>Conway's Maritime Editors</nowiki>|title=Conway's All the World's Fighting Ships 1922\u20131946|year=1980|location=Annapolis, MD|publisher=Naval Institute Press|isbn=0-87021-913-8|ref={{SfnRef|Conway's|1980}}}}\n*{{cite book|last=Friedman|first=Norman|year=2004|title=U.S. Destroyers|location=Annapolis, MD|publisher=Naval Institute Press|isbn=978-1-55750-442-5|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite magazine|url=http://www.evolutionunderwater.com/uss-tucker|title=USS Tucker: A Prestigious Past with an Inglorious End|last=Gerken|first=Mike|magazine=Wreck Diving Magazine|issue=31|date=2013|accessdate=27 October 2019|via=EvolutionUnderwater.com|ref={{sfnref|Gerken|2013}}}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Hodges|first1=Peter|last2=Friedman|first2= Norman|year=1979|title=Destroyer Weapons of World War 2|location=Annapolis, MD|publisher=Naval Institute Press|isbn=0-87021-929-4|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite web|author=NHHC|title=Tucker|url=http://www.history.navy.mil/research/histories/ship-histories/danfs/t/tucker-dd-374-ii.html|publisher=[[Naval History and Heritage Command]]|accessdate=26 April 2016|ref={{SfnRef|NHHC}}}}\n*{{cite book|last=Parkin|first=Robert Sinclair|title=Blood on the Sea: American Destroyers Lost in World War II|url=https://archive.org/details/bloodonseaameric00park|url-access=registration|date=1996|publisher=Sarpedon|location=New York, NY|isbn=1-885119-17-8|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Reilly|first=John|date=1983|title=United States Navy Destroyers of World War II|location=Poole, Dorset, England|publisher=Blandford Press|isbn=0-7137-1026-8|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/unitedstatesnavy0000reil}}\n*{{cite book|last=Roscoe|first=Theodore|title=U.S. Destroyer  Operations in World War II|date=1953|publisher=Naval Institute Press|location=Annapolis, MD|isbn=0-87021-726-7|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/unitedstatesdest0000rosc}}\n*{{cite book|last=Rohwer|first=J\u00fcrgen|title=Chronology of the War at Sea 1939\u20131945|date=2005|publisher=Naval Institute Press|location=Annapolis, MD|isbn=1-59114-119-2|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Stone|first=Peter|title=The Lady and the President: The Life and Loss of the S. S. President Coolidge|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=THyca-AHdOEC&pg=PA79|year=1997|publisher=Oceans Enterprises|location=Yarram, Australia|isbn=978-0-95866572-8|ref=harv}}\n*{{DANFS|http://www.history.navy.mil/research/histories/ship-histories/danfs/t/tucker-dd-374-ii.html}}\n\n===External links===\n*{{cite web |last1=Stone (2)|first1=Peter |title=The Lady and the President, The Life and Loss of the SS President Coolidge |url=http://www.oceans.com.au/pc.html |publisher=Oceans Enterprises |accessdate=24 November 2019}}\n{{Mahan class destroyer}}\n{{August 1942 shipwrecks}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tucker (DD-374)}}\n[[Category:1936 ships]]\n[[Category:Attack on Pearl Harbor]]\n[[Category:Mahan-class destroyers]]\n[[Category:Maritime incidents in August 1942]]\n[[Category:Ships built in Portsmouth, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Ships present during the attack on Pearl Harbor]]\n[[Category:Ships sunk by mines]]\n[[Category:United States Navy Massachusetts-related ships]]\n[[Category:World War II destroyers of the United States]]\n[[Category:World War II shipwrecks in the Pacific Ocean]]\n", "text_old": "{{other ships|USS Tucker}}\n{{short description|Mahan-class destroyer}}\n{{coord missing|Pacific Ocean}}\n{{good article}}\n{|{{Infobox ship begin}}\n{{Infobox ship image\n|Ship image=Uss Tucker DD-374.jpg\n|Ship caption=USS ''Tucker'' off the [[Norfolk Navy Yard]], [[Portsmouth, Virginia]], 2{{nbsp}}March 1937\n}}\n{{Infobox ship career\n|Hide header=\n|Ship country=United States\n|Ship flag={{USN flag|1942}}\n|Ship name=''Tucker''\n|Ship namesake=[[Samuel Tucker]]\n|Ship ordered=\n|Ship builder=[[Norfolk Navy Yard]]\n|Ship laid down=15 August 1934\n|Ship launched=26 February 1936\n|Ship commissioned=23 July 1936\n|Ship struck=2 December 1944\n|Ship honours=\n|Ship fate=Struck [[Naval mine|mine]] off [[Espiritu Santo]], [[New Hebrides]], 4{{nbsp}}August 1942\n|Ship status=\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n{{Infobox ship characteristics\n|Hide header=\n|Header caption=(as built)\n|Ship class={{sclass-|Mahan|destroyer}}\n|Ship displacement=*{{convert|1500|LT|t|0|lk=in}} ([[standard load]])\n*{{convert|1725|LT|t}} ([[deep load]])\n|Ship length={{convert|341|ft|m|abbr=on|1}}\n|Ship beam={{convert|35|ft|6|in|m|abbr=on|1}}\n|Ship draft={{convert|10|ft|7|in|m|abbr=on|1}}\n|Ship power=*{{convert|46,000|shp|lk=on}}\n*4 [[water-tube boiler]]s           \n|Ship propulsion=2 [[shafts]] 2 geared [[steam turbine]]s\n|Ship speed={{convert|37|kn|lk=in}}\n|Ship range={{convert|6940|nmi|lk=in|abbr=on}} at {{convert|12|kn}}\n|Ship complement=158 officers and enlisted men\n|Ship sensors=*1 \u00d7 [[gun director]] above bridge\n|Ship armament=*5 \u00d7 single [[5\"/38 caliber gun|{{convert|5|in|mm|abbr=on|0}}]] [[DP gun]]s\n*3 \u00d7 quadruple [[American 21 inch torpedo|21 in (533 mm)]] [[torpedo tube]]s\n*4 \u00d7 single [[M2 Browning|.50 cal (12.7 mm)]] AA machine guns\n*2 \u00d7 [[depth charge]] stern racks\n*Depth charge projectors (aka [[K-guns]])\n|Ship notes=\n}}\n|}\n\n'''USS ''Tucker'' (DD-374)''' was a {{sclass-|Mahan|destroyer}} of the [[United States Navy]] and was commissioned in 1936. ''Tucker''{{'}}s [[main battery]] consisted of five [[Dual-purpose gun|dual-purpose]] [[38 caliber 5-inch (127 mm) guns]].\n\nFirst assigned to the [[United States Battle Fleet]] in San Diego, California, ''Tucker'' operated along the [[West Coast of the United States|West Coast]] and in the [[Hawaiian Islands]]. After participating in [[naval exercise]]s in the [[Caribbean Sea]], she returned to duty in [[Territory of Hawaii|Hawaii]]. She then went on a goodwill tour to New Zealand, returning to Hawaii and docking at [[Pearl Harbor]]. When the [[Empire of Japan|Japanese]] [[Attack on Pearl Harbor|attacked Pearl Harbor]] on 7{{nbsp}}December 1941, ''Tucker'' was undergoing an overhaul but sustained no damage. Soon afterward, she  began escorting convoys between the West Coast and Hawaii. ''Tucker'' was then tasked with escort duty to islands in the [[South Pacific Ocean|Sourth Pacific]].\n\n''Tucker'' steamed out of port on 1 August 1942, escorting a cargo ship to [[Espiritu Santo]]. They entered its harbor on 4 August, where they had, unknowingly, moved into a [[minefield]] laid by the US Navy. ''Tucker'' struck at least one [[Naval mine|mine]] and was torn almost in two, killing three sailors. The rest of the crew survived but the destroyer sank. ''Tucker'' had not been informed of the minefield. \n\n==Design==\n\n===General characteristics===  \n''Tucker'' [[Displacement (ship)|displaced]] {{cvt|1500|LT|t|0|lk=on}}\nat [[standard load]] and {{convert|1725|LT|t}} at [[deep load]]. The ship's [[length overall|overall length]] was {{convert|341|ft|m|1}}, her [[beam (nautical)|beam]] was {{convert|35|ft|6|in|m|1}}, and her [[draft (hull)|draft]] was {{convert|10|ft|7|in|m|1}}. Her peace-time complement was 158 officers and enlisted men.{{sfn|Friedman|2004|pp=465\u2013466}}\n\nShe had a [[Tripod mast|tripod]] [[foremast]] and a pole mainmast. To improve the [[antiaircraft]] [[field of fire (weaponry)|field of fire]], her [[tripod]] foremast was constructed without nautical [[rigging]].{{sfn|Friedman|2004|p=88}} The destroyer was fitted with emergency [[diesel generators]], replacing the storage batteries of earlier destroyers. Gun crew shelters were also built fore and aft for the superimposed guns. A third set of quadruple [[torpedo tubes]] was added, with one mounted on the [[centerline]] and two in the side positions.{{sfn |Friedman|2004|p=88}}\n\n===Machinery and armament===\n''Tucker'' was fitted with four [[water-tube boiler]]s built by either [[Babcock & Wilcox]] or [[Foster Wheeler]]. They generated the steam that propelled the two [[General Electric]] geared [[steam turbine]]s, developing {{convert|46,000|shp|abbr=on|lk=on}} for a maximum speed of {{convert|37|kn|lk=in}}. ''Tucker'' carried a maximum of {{convert|523|LT|t}} of [[fuel oil]], with a trial range of {{convert|7300|nmi|lk=in}} at {{convert|12|kn|lk=in}}. The ship's\nwartime ranges were {{convert|6940|nmi|lk=in}} at {{convert|12|kn|lk=in}} and {{convert|4360|nmi|lk=in}} at {{convert|20|kn|lk=in}}.\nThe ship's design incorporated a new generation of land-based propulsion machinery. The boilers were capable of reaching {{convert|650\u2013700|F|C|sigfig=2}}, powering the high-pressure turbines with [[double reduction gearing|double reduction gears]] that enabled the turbines to run faster and more efficiently than in previous destroyer designs.{{sfn|Friedman|2004|p=88}}\n\n''Tucker''{{'}}s [[main battery]] consisted of five [[Dual-purpose gun|dual-purpose]] [[38 caliber 5-inch (127 mm) guns]], equipped with the MK{{nbsp}}33 gun [[fire-control system]].{{sfn|Friedman|2004|p=465}} Each gun was configured for surface and aerial targets.{{sfn |Friedman|2004| p=88}} The ship's antiaircraft battery had four water-cooled [[.50 caliber machine gun]]s (12.7&nbsp;mm).{{sfn|Hodges|Friedman|1979|p=111}} The ship was fitted with three quadruple torpedo-tube mounts for twelve {{convert|21|in|mm|adj=on|0}} [[torpedo]]es, guided by the Mark{{nbsp}}27 torpedo fire-control system.{{sfn|Friedman|2004|p=465}} She was rigged for two [[depth charge]] roll-off racks and for depth charge projectors (K-guns).{{sfn|Friedman|2004|p=86}} In early 1942, the Navy began to refit the ''Mahan''-class destroyers with new antiaircraft armament, although most of the class was not refitted until sometime in 1944.{{sfn|Hodges|Friedman|1979|p=145}}\n\n==Construction and service history==\n\n''Tucker'' was one of eighteen [[Mahan-class destroyer|Mahan-class destroyers]] and was built at the [[Norfolk Navy Yard]] in [[Portsmouth, Virginia]].{{sfn|Conway's|1980|pp=125\u2013126}} She was the second vessel to be named for [[Samuel Tucker]], who had been an officer in the [[Continental Navy]] and the United States Navy.{{sfn|Parkin|1996|p=67}} ''Tucker''{{'}}s [[keel]] was laid down on 15{{nbsp}}August 1934. She was [[Ceremonial ship launching|launched]] on 26{{nbsp}}February 1936 and [[Christening|christened]] by a third cousin of Tucker. The ship was commissioned in the United States Navy on 23{{nbsp}}July, with [[Lieutenant commander (United States)|Lieutenant Commander]] George T. Howard in command.{{sfn|Parkin|1996|p=68-69}}\n\n[[File:USS Tucker.jpg|thumb|alt=Naval warship rigged with sails|''Tucker'' rigged with sails, June 1940]]\nAfter her [[shakedown cruise]], she joined destroyer forces attached to the United States Battle Fleet in [[San Diego]], [[California]]. She operated with them along the West Coast and in the Hawaiian islands as part of Destroyer Squadron{{nbsp}}3 of the Destroyer Division.\nIn February 1939, she took part in [[Fleet Problem&nbsp;XX]], a naval exercise held in the Caribbean Sea and Atlantic Ocean and observed by President [[Franklin D. Roosevelt]]. As tensions with Japan increased, the fleet was ordered to return to Hawaiian waters.{{sfn|NHHC}}\n\nIn June 1940, ''Tucker'' steamed from Hawaii to a location east of [[Wake Island]] for fleet exercises. In ''United States Navy Destroyers of World War II,'' John Reilly, Jr. described the uncommon method used to power the vessel on its return to Hawaii: {{blockquote|... Tucker stretched her fuel supply by rigging Sails. Her homemade [[foresail]] and [[mainsail]] moved Tucker at an estimated 3.4 knots, letting her maintain [[Glossary of nautical terms#steerageway|steerageway]] as she loitered on station several days.{{sfn|Reilly|1983|p=30}}}}\n\n''Tucker'' continued operating between Hawaii and the West Coast into February 1941. She then set course for New Zealand on a goodwill tour, arriving in [[Auckland]] on 17 March. Returning to Pearl Harbor, she took part in routine exercises at sea before returning to her homeport of San Diego on 19{{nbsp}}September. After a short stay, ''Tucker'' steamed to Hawaii in November as part of Task Force{{nbsp}}19, operating again in the Hawaiian Islands. Shortly afterward, she put into Pearl Harbor for an overhaul by a [[destroyer tender]].{{sfn|NHHC}}\n\nWhen the [[Empire of Japan|Japanese]] [[Attack on Pearl Harbor|attacked Pearl Harbor]] on 7 December 1941, ''Tucker'' was one of five destroyers moored at berth X\u20139, East Loch, alongside the destroyer tender {{USS|Whitney|AD-4|2}}.{{sfn|Roscoe|1953|pp=47\u201348}} Even before ''Tucker''{{'}}s [[general quarters]] alarm could be sounded, one of her on-deck sailors began firing a 50-caliber machine gun at the first wave of Japanese aircraft. When the second wave attacked, every ship that could opened fire. ''Tucker''{{'}}s gunners scored hits on at least two aircraft: one crashed in a cane field, another in flames disappeared over a mountaintop. Because ''Tucker'' was at Pearl Harbor for overhaul, much of her machinery had been torn down for repairs; despite the crew's efforts, they were unable to get the ship underway until that evening.{{sfn|Parkin|1996|p=68}}\n\nAfter her overhaul, ''Tucker'' patrolled off Pearl Harbor and spent several months escorting convoys between Hawaii and the West Coast. With new orders, she steamed to the South Pacific for convoy duty. ''Tucker'' then escorted the auxiliary ship {{USS|Wright|AV-1|2}} to [[Tutuila]], [[American Samoa]], as part of the drive to fortify outposts. She then escorted her charge to [[Suva]], [[British Fiji|Fiji]], and proceeded to [[Noumea]], [[New Caledonia]]. Steaming on for Australia, she arrived at [[Sydney]] on 27{{nbsp}}April. After taking on fuel, she visited [[Melbourne]], [[Perth, Western Australia|Perth]], and [[Fremantle, Western Australia|Fremantle]] before steaming back to Sydney. ''Tucker'' and  ''Wright'' returned to Suva, arriving on 3{{nbsp}}June 1942. For the remainder of June and into the first week of July, ''Tucker'' operated out of Suva before relieving the cruiser {{USS|Boise|CL-47|2}} of convoy escort duties on 10{{nbsp}}July. On{{nbsp}}30 July, the ship arrived at Auckland and the following day started back for Suva.{{sfn|NHHC}}\n\n==Fate==\n[[Image:DD-374 sunk 5Aug1942 EspirituSanto NAN09-10-86.jpg|thumb|alt=Naval ship struck by a mine and sinking|USS ''Tucker'' (D-374) sinking south of Espiritu Santo,  5 August 1942]]\n\nOn 1{{nbsp}}August 1942 ''Tucker'' left Suva, escorting the cargo ship SS ''Nira Luckenbach'' to [[Espiritu Santo]], [[New Hebrides]].{{sfn|NHHC}} On 4{{nbsp}}August ''Tucker'' led the cargo ship into the harbor at Espiritu Santo, as she headed into the western entrance, she struck at least one [[Naval mine|mine]]. The explosion tore her hull nearly in two at the [[Funnel (ship)|No.{{nbsp}}1 stack]], killing all three crew members on watch in the forward [[fire room]]. The rest of the ship's company survived.\n''Nira Luckenbach'' and other vessels rescued sailors from their sinking ship. ''Tucker''{{'}}s [[stern]] sank the following morning; a diving party scuttled and sank her [[bow (ship)|bow]].{{sfn|Roscoe|1953|p=165}} The ship had steamed into the [[Segond Channel]] unaware that the minelayers {{USS|Gamble|DD-123|2}}, {{USS|Breese|DD-122|2}}, and {{USS|Tracy|DD-214|2}} had laid mines at its western entrance. An investigation revealed that ''Tucker's'' captain had not been informed of the minefield.{{sfn|Rohwer|2005|p=184}} She was stricken from the ''[[Naval Vessel Register]]'' on 2{{nbsp}}December 1944.{{sfn|NHHC}} ''Tucker''{{'}}s loss was a setback to the [[United States Pacific Fleet|Pacific Fleet]], which was trying to assemble every available ship for the [[Battle of Guadalcanal]].{{sfn|Roscoe|1953|p=165}}\n\nThree days after ''Tucker'' sank, the seagoing tugboat {{USS|Navajo|AT-64|2}} arrived on site with divers, [[marine salvage|salvaging]] her guns, turbines, anchors and chains. During the remainder of the war, the Navy used the wreckage site for diver training; they did not undertake further salvaging. \nSettling in just {{convert|60|ft}} of water, the ship was easily accessible to private salvors, who harvested anything of value, ransacking and further scattering ''Tucker''{{'}}s remains. Sport divers also had a destructive effect on the site, which by 1997 resembled an \"underwater junkyard\".{{sfn|Stone|1997|pp=78\u201379}} Mike Gerken, an underwater photojournalist, dove the ''Tucker'' wreckage site several times; in 2013 he eulogized ''Tucker'' and other sunken ships:\n\n{{quote\n|text=To see a ship with a distinguished record as the ''Tucker'' in such a poor state gave me pause for thought. I pondered that wrecks, like the ''Tucker'', will gradually disappear and to be saddened by this inevitable fact would be pointless. What is important is that the memory of these ships be kept alive by telling their stories.\n|author=Mike Gerken\n|title=\"The USS ''Tucker'': A Prestigious Past with an Inglorious End\"\n|source=''Wreck Diving Magazine''{{sfn|Gerken|2013}}\n}}\n\n''Tucker'' and [[SS President Coolidge|SS ''President Coolidge'']], a troopship, suffered similar fates less than three months apart; both were sunk in different locations of the same U.S. Navy minefield, and both later became diving sites.{{sfn|Gerken|2013}}\n\n==Honors==\n''Tucker'' received one [[battle star]] for her [[World War II]] service.{{sfn|Parkin|1996|p=69}}\n\n==References==\n===Citations===\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n===Bibliography===\n*{{cite book|author=<nowiki>Conway's Maritime Editors</nowiki>|title=Conway's All the World's Fighting Ships 1922\u20131946|year=1980|location=Annapolis, MD|publisher=Naval Institute Press|isbn=0-87021-913-8|ref={{SfnRef|Conway's|1980}}}}\n*{{cite book|last=Friedman|first=Norman|year=2004|title=U.S. Destroyers|location=Annapolis, MD|publisher=Naval Institute Press|isbn=978-1-55750-442-5|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite magazine|url=http://www.evolutionunderwater.com/uss-tucker|title=USS Tucker: A Prestigious Past with an Inglorious End|last=Gerken|first=Mike|magazine=Wreck Diving Magazine|issue=31|date=2013|accessdate=27 October 2019|via=EvolutionUnderwater.com|ref={{sfnref|Gerken|2013}}}}\n*{{cite book|last1=Hodges|first1=Peter|last2=Friedman|first2= Norman|year=1979|title=Destroyer Weapons of World War 2|location=Annapolis, MD|publisher=Naval Institute Press|isbn=0-87021-929-4|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite web|author=NHHC|title=Tucker|url=http://www.history.navy.mil/research/histories/ship-histories/danfs/t/tucker-dd-374-ii.html|publisher=[[Naval History and Heritage Command]]|accessdate=26 April 2016|ref={{SfnRef|NHHC}}}}\n*{{cite book|last=Parkin|first=Robert Sinclair|title=Blood on the Sea: American Destroyers Lost in World War II|url=https://archive.org/details/bloodonseaameric00park|url-access=registration|date=1996|publisher=Sarpedon|location=New York, NY|isbn=1-885119-17-8|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Reilly|first=John|date=1983|title=United States Navy Destroyers of World War II|location=Poole, Dorset, England|publisher=Blandford Press|isbn=0-7137-1026-8|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/unitedstatesnavy0000reil}}\n*{{cite book|last=Roscoe|first=Theodore|title=U.S. Destroyer  Operations in World War II|date=1953|publisher=Naval Institute Press|location=Annapolis, MD|isbn=0-87021-726-7|ref=harv|url-access=registration|url=https://archive.org/details/unitedstatesdest0000rosc}}\n*{{cite book|last=Rohwer|first=J\u00fcrgen|title=Chronology of the War at Sea 1939\u20131945|date=2005|publisher=Naval Institute Press|location=Annapolis, MD|isbn=1-59114-119-2|ref=harv}}\n*{{cite book|last=Stone|first=Peter|title=The Lady and the President: The Life and Loss of the S. S. President Coolidge|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=THyca-AHdOEC&pg=PA79|year=1997|publisher=Oceans 